arXiv:2603.25016v2 Announce Type: replace Abstract: The hydrodynamic formulation of quantum mechanics features two velocity fields: a geodesic (classical) velocity $\pi_{\mu}$ and a stochastic (quantum) velocity $u_{\mu}$. We show that averaging over a stochastic gravitational wave background unifies these into a single complex velocity $\eta_{\mu}=\pi_{\mu}-iu_{\mu}$, derived from the logarithmic derivative of a matter amplitude $\mathcal{K}$. This object lives as a section of the pullback bundle $\pi_{2}^{*}(T^{*}M)$ over configuration space and defines a flat $U(1)$ connection, satisfying $D_{\mu}\mathcal{K}=0$. Crucially, $\eta_{\mu}$ acts as a fundamental information-geometric carrier, where $u_{\mu}$ maps the variance of metric fluctuations $\langle h_{\mu
u}h_{\alpha eta}angle$ to the Fisher metric and von Neumann entropy. The resulting geometric structure collapses into an elegant complex geodesic equation $\eta^{
